	<dialogues>
		<dialogue>
			<topText>This is Thomas, a common business man with a wife and three children at home.</topText>
			<bottomText>1916</bottomText>
			<stageX>0</stageX>
		</dialogue>
		<dialogue>
		  <topText>As Thomas walked through the bustling town, his eyes kept glancing at the persuasive propaganda posters around him.</topText>
		    <topText>Each poster was bright, and made the war seem like an easy experience.</topText>
			<bottomText>April 6, 1917</bottomText>
			<stageX>852</stageX>
		</dialogue>
		<dialogue>
          <topText>With each new poster, the gears in his mind began to turn. "Maybe enlisting wouldn't be a bad idea after all," he thought.</topText>
            <topText>But was it really worth leaving his family?</topText>
            <topText> </topText>
            <topText>He felt that he owed it to his country to join the army; almost like he had no choice.</topText>
            <bottomText></bottomText>
            <stageX>1400</stageX>
        </dialogue>
        <dialogue>
          <topText>After thinking long and hard, his mind was set. He would join the war...</topText>
            <topText> </topText>
            <topText>...even if it meant leaving the love of his life and their children behind.</topText>
            <bottomText></bottomText>
            <stageX>1904</stageX>
        </dialogue>
	</dialogues>
